<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>down on someone • down to someone</xh5><p> <i>down on someone</i>—(coll.) expressing strong disapproval of smb.; reprimanding a person severely: “They’re <u>down on</u> her for some reason or other,” he told himself. “Angry, most likely, because she’s hung on to her boy.”</p><p> <i>down to someone—</i>being the responsibility of smb.; being incumbent upon a person: You need to be a good communicator to get your business vision across. Remember the success of your business is <u>down to</u> you.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression is not antonymous in meaning to the phrase <b>up to someone</b>— = down to someone: The success of your business is <u>up to</u> you, your efforts and your commitment.</p> </entry>
